metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 3 #101
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ - Iteration 1, ____ - Iteration 2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: Trasiedoc #393
metadata.description:
Behind every generative art project is a code. This code is sometimes a masterpiece but most viewers do not see it.

With the Trasiedoc project I wanted to highlight the hidden face of generative art, the code, by literally integrating the code of my biggest project to date (Dencity) in each output of the Trasiedoc project.

Margins can be hidden by pressing "x" in live mode (and optionally press "p" to see if anything happens).

Made with ❤️, code, code and p5js.

metadata.name: AI Brain Scheme #22
metadata.description:
Simple project using trigonometry, recursive function 
and simple geometry shapes to create an imaginary AI Brain Scheme

You can download the large image to see the small detail.

---
Features : 
AI Grid Configurator : True/False
AI Extra Brain Chips : True/False
Ai Binary Dreams Code : True/False
Photonic Wire : True/False

AI Level : 9 Levels (Very Small AI-Small AI-Medium AI-Medium x2 AI-Large AI-Large x2 AI-Impossible AI-Insane AI-Quantum Level AI)
"Quantum Level AI" = super rare

Color Schemes : red,blue,green
---
Unlimited colors palette
---
Press [p] to save captured image to png (3300pxx4500px)
---
Created using vanilla javascript

metadata.name: Obliques #183
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: Sub Section Patina #833
metadata.description:
"Sub Section Patina" is inspired by street art and the marks and layering from that art form. If you zoom in on a small section of a wall that artists have marked, sprayed paint, and plastered with posters, some beautiful effects start to happen.

While the "Sub Section Patina" layers are building up, there is a tendency to destroy the layers below. The layering is similar to a wall many street artists have contributed. Sometimes just a section will be covered and filled with something else. Sometimes large areas of the canvas are covered up. Other layers will be put on top of one another, creating a new chaotic image. 

Features:
Four different sizes: 9x16, 11x14", 12x18", 12x12"
Portrait or landscape orientation
~500 color pallets, one black and white, one cyan, magenta, yellow and black, and the rest from Jam3/nice-color-palettes.

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
substack/point-in-polygon

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: Acid Warning #22
metadata.description:
Acid Warning is an algorithm that generates LSD warning labels.  When Bear and his students were setting up their Richmond acid lab they commissioned this series of warning label designs for their equipment.

The artwork was abandoned as the chemists quickly found it impossible to avoid getting high while working in the lab. Instead of labeling their laboratory gear, they all embraced the “Acid Makers’ Queasy” for weeks on end.  This generative psychedelia project is a reprint of the Bear’s lost Acid Warning series.    

- Double click to enable turntable mode
- Click and drag and zoom to move around in 3D
- Don’t take too much acid in real life homies!

Created by @capnganj - one love <3

metadata.name: WAR #108
metadata.description:
We are constantly warring, often times with ourselves, sometimes with others, but mostly with what we even don't know. This needs to stop, and it shall stop by the following terms:

I.   We shall never accept wins, depending on others' losses.
II.  We shall never accept life, sucked out of others' deaths.
III. We shall never accept prosperity, originated from others' poverty.
IV.  We shall never accept happiness, sourced from others' misery.
V.   We shall never accept civilization, built upon others' devastation.

Signed I I · · I I

* * *

D: Hide Tag
G: Hide Grain
S: Save PNG
